'''Istind Peak''' ({{coord|72|6|S|2|23|W|}}) is a partly ice-covered [[Summit (topography)|peak]] 1 mile (1.6&nbsp;km) south of [[Tindeklypa]], on the east side of [[Ahlmann Ridge]] in [[Queen Maud Land]]. Photographed from the air by the [[Third German Antarctic Expedition]] (1938â39). Mapped by Norwegian cartographers from air photos by the [[Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition]] (NBSAE) (1949â1952), led by [[John Schjelderup GiÃ¦ver]] and air photos by the Norwegian expedition (1958â59) and named "Istind" (ice tooth).

An unsuccessful attempt to climb this impressive mountain was made by [[Duncan Cromarty]] and [[Karel Koster]] in November 1999. Both climbers were members of the [[SANAE]] 38 overwintering team.

